			<tr>
				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Greetings New Bard, New player, Lap Top Issues<a name="50195"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Jul 5 04 10:23 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span><blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">
<br />
Well, what I meant is that GF4 cards don't support DX9 specific features. I realize that they will run DX9 games.
<br />
</span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
Well, they're not fully DX9-<i>compliant</i>, no.
<br />
To be fully DX9-compliant, a card needs to support pixel shaders (PS) 2.0 and vertex shaders (VS) 2.0 (among other things). Most Geforce4s (the TIs and the newer GOs) support PS 1.3 and VS 1.1, which makes them DX9-compatible. Some GF4s (the MXs and older GOs) don't support PS or VS which makes them incompatible with DX9. For a game to run the current Everquest engine it needs to support at least PS 1.3 and VS 1.1.
<br />

<br />
There's a really good <a target="_new" href="http://eqiiforums.station.sony.com/eq2/board/message?board.id=tech_support&amp;message.id=211&amp;view=by_date_ascending&amp;page=1">unofficial list of EQ2 supported cards</a>. A general rule of thumb is that if the card can run EQ2, it can run EQ1 DX9.
<br />

<br />
The one thing that confuses me is that there's no such thing AFAIK as a Geforce4 <i>48</i> GO. But I guess it doesn't matter, it's working now.</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
